# Contribution Guidelines
Thank you for your interest in contributing to this project! We welcome and appreciate any kind of contribution, whether it is code, documentation, bug reports, feature requests, or feedback. Please follow these guidelines to make the process easier and more effective for everyone involved.


## Code of Conduct
We support the official [code of conduct](https://dotnetfoundation.org/about/policies/code-of-conduct) defined by the .NET Foundation organization.

Please read it and follow before you interact with the project community. We expect all contributors to respect each other and foster a positive and inclusive environment.


## How to Contribute
There are many ways you can contribute to this project, depending on your skills, interests, and availability. Here are some common ways:

### Report bugs
If you encounter any issues or errors while using the project, please create an issue on GitHub and describe what happened. Include as much detail as possible, such as the steps to reproduce the bug, the expected and actual behaviour, and any error messages or screenshots. This will help us diagnose and fix the problem faster.

### Suggest features
If you have an idea for a new or improved feature for the project, please create an issue on GitHub and outline your proposal. Explain what the feature is, why it is useful or necessary, and how it should work. We will review your suggestion and discuss it with you.

### Write code
If you want to implement a bug fix or a feature yourself, feel free to do so and create a pull request on GitHub . Also, please write a clear and concise commit message and pull request description that explains what you did and why.

Ensure in addition the following:
1. That the current code structure is not compromised.
2. Make sure you follow the code style and testing guidelines for the project
3. That every existing test case is properly passing.
4. That new test cases are added to support the new functionality, or modified the existing ones accordingly.
5. That you follow the comments and advices commented by code owners during the code review of the PR process.
6. That you properly adapt the documentation in the corresponding README file if needed, and add the proper release notes in the proper changelog file.


### Review code
If you have some experience with the project or the technologies involved, you can help us improve the quality of our code by reviewing other people's pull requests. You can provide feedback on the code style, logic, functionality, documentation, tests, or anything else you think is relevant. Please be constructive and respectful in your comments.

### Write documentation
If you have expertise or interest in the project's domain, you can help us improve our documentation by writing or editing content for the README, wiki, or website. You can also create tutorials, guides, examples, or FAQs that demonstrate how to use the project effectively.

### Spread the word
If you like the project and find it useful or interesting, you can support us by sharing it with others who might benefit from it. You can also star the project on GitHub or give us feedback on what you like or dislike about it.


**Thank you for being part of this! :raised_hands:**